{"author":{"id":"cc8322a500b8739c77faac347808f6026d9ccb7880d0aaa7ad76754163cd7fdb"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782568926,"nonce":"PkdkpoSAs0qRfAaEq45v6EsWY5w=","kind":"spec","title":"Idempotent Marker-Based Ingest \u0026 Spec-Tooling Auto-Capture — Design"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782568926,"nonce":"KOUF72a7Sx0lIF4S7tnGTna/3As=","body":"# Idempotent Marker-Based Ingest \u0026 Spec-Tooling Auto-Capture — Design\n\n- **Date:** 2026-06-17\n- **Status:** Draft (pending author review)\n- **Type:** Feature design (extends the Phase-1 ingest bridge)\n- **Builds on:** [`2026-06-16-git-native-knowledge-base-design.md`](2026-06-16-git-native-knowledge-base-design.md) §1 (the bridge), §6 (ingest)\n\n\u003e This realizes the \"bridge that lets existing file-writing tools keep working\n\u003e while their output lives in the store\" from the architecture spec (§1, §6).\n\u003e It does **not** change the storage model, tiers, or sync.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Problem\n\n`kref ingest \u003cpath\u003e` (Phase 1) always **creates a new entry**. Two consequences\nblock the bridge's intended use — auto-capturing spec-tooling output\n(superpowers, speckit, openspec) into the store:\n\n1. **No idempotency.** Re-ingesting a file produces a duplicate entry. Spec\n   artifacts mutate as people iterate, so any commit-triggered capture would\n   spawn a pile of duplicates for one logical document.\n2. **No identity continuity.** Nothing links a working-tree file to the entry\n   it already produced, so kref cannot tell \"update the plan I already have\" from\n   \"here is a new plan.\"\n\nThe Phase-1 generated `post-commit` hook (`kref ingest`, no argument) is also\ninert — `ingest` requires exactly one path, so the hook errors on every commit.\n\n## 2. Goals\n\n- Re-ingesting a file **updates the same entry** (append a body/title op to its\n  op-DAG) rather than creating a duplicate.\n- Identity survives **edits, moves, and renames** of the source file.\n- A single generated hook captures the conventional output of superpowers,\n  speckit, and openspec **on commit**, working in any repo (present or absent\n  dirs), with **no working-tree deletion** (gitignore-mirror, not delete +\n  materialize).\n- Preserve every Phase-1 safety property: gitleaks fail-closed, secret\n  quarantine to `private`, the structurally-unpushable private tier.\n\n## 3. Non-Goals (this feature)\n\n- `kref checkout` / materialize-from-store. We are **not** deleting the source\n  file, so no round-trip checkout is needed (deferred; see §9).\n- Force-gitignoring `specs/` / `openspec/`. kref does not impose tree policy on\n  the user's spec dirs (superpowers already gitignores its own).\n- Semantic search, encryption at rest — unchanged from the architecture spec's\n  deferred list.\n\n## 4. Decisions\n\n### D1 — Identity is an embedded trailer marker, not the source path\n\nA trailer line is appended to the end of an ingested file, on its own line\nafter a blank line:\n\n```\n\u003c!-- kref-id: \u003c64-hex-entity-id\u003e --\u003e\n```\n\n- **Why a trailer HTML comment, not YAML front-matter:** front-matter must be\n  the *first* line of the file and would collide with speckit/openspec files\n  that carry their own front-matter. A trailing HTML comment is valid markdown\n  anywhere, renders invisibly, and is trivial to append and strip.\n- **Why an embedded marker, not the file path:** a path-keyed index breaks the\n  moment a file is moved or renamed (a routine refactor for spec dirs),\n  producing a duplicate. The marker travels *in* the file.\n- **No entry schema change.** The file carries its own identity; the store gains\n  only an \"append body/title to an existing id\" path. The entity `Id()` is\n  derived from the `Create` op and is stable across later ops (confirmed in\n  `internal/entry/operations.go`), so the id minted at creation is permanent.\n\n### D2 — Per-file ingest state machine\n\nFor each file, after stripping the trailer marker to get the stored body:\n\n| Marker | gitleaks | Existing entry | Action |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| absent | clean | — | **create** in requested tier; stamp marker → `created` |\n| absent | secret | — | **create** in `private` (quarantine); stamp marker; warn → `quarantined` |\n| present | clean | found, body+title unchanged | **no-op** → `unchanged` |\n| present | clean | found, changed | append `SetBody`/`SetTitle` → `updated` |\n| present | clean | missing (purged) | treat as create; re-stamp → `created` |\n| present | **secret** | found | **`error`, fail closed** (see D3, §7) |\n\n### D3 — Secret on an already-mapped file fails closed\n\nIf gitleaks trips on a file that already carries a `kref-id` marker, kref **refuses\nto update** and returns an error. Rationale: the mapped entry may live in a\nsyncable tier (`personal`/`shared`); silently appending the secret would push it\nto a remote — the exact leak quarantine exists to prevent. We cannot \"move\" an\nentry between tier namespaces cheaply, so the safe action is to stop and tell\nthe user to rotate the secret and `purge` (then re-ingest). The unmarked-file\nquarantine path (create in `private`) is unchanged from Phase 1.\n\n### D4 — Title updates need a `SetTitle` op\n\nPhase 1 sets the title only at `Create`. To keep the mirror faithful when a\ndocument's H1 changes, add a `SetTitle` operation (mirrors `SetBody`: const,\nstruct, `Id`/`Validate`/`Apply`, unmarshaler registration, constructor — the\n4-step recipe in `docs/dev/README.md`). On update, append `SetTitle` only when\nthe derived title actually changed.\n\n### D5 — `kref ingest` accepts multiple paths and directories\n\n- Signature: `kref ingest \u003cpath\u003e...` (≥1 path).\n- A **directory** argument is walked recursively for `*.md`, skipping `.git/`\n  and `.kref/`. Each file runs the D2 state machine.\n- New `--skip-missing` flag: a non-existent path becomes a skip-with-note\n  instead of an error. The generated hook sets it so one config works whether or\n  not a given spec dir exists; an interactive `kref ingest missing.md` (no flag)\n  still errors, preserving CLI strictness.\n- Output becomes a JSON **array** of `{path, id, title, tier, action}` (was a\n  single object). `action` ∈\n  `created|updated|unchanged|quarantined|error` (see §7 for `error`).\n\n### D6 — Generated hook: changed markdown in the usual-suspect dirs, no deletion\n\nReplaces the broken `post-commit` block. It captures only files **changed in the\nlast commit** (cheap; avoids re-scanning the whole tree every commit) and only\nwithin the conventional dirs. The dir scoping is a **git pathspec** on the\n`files:` command and the markdown filter is a **single-pattern** `glob` — both\nwork on every lefthook version (list-form `glob` would require lefthook\n≥1.10.10, verified, so it is avoided):\n\n```yaml\npost-commit:\n  commands:\n    kref-ingest:\n      files: git diff-tree --no-commit-id --name-only -r HEAD -- docs/superpowers/plans specs .specify openspec\n      glob: \"*.md\"\n      run: \u003cabs-kref\u003e ingest --skip-missing {files}\n```\n\n- `files:` returns the paths changed in the new commit, restricted by git\n  pathspec to the four spec dirs; `glob: \"*.md\"` keeps only markdown; `{files}`\n  expands to that set. When it is empty, lefthook skips the command, so commits\n  that touch no spec markdown are a true no-op.\n- `--skip-missing` absorbs paths that `diff-tree` reports as **deleted** (they\n  no longer exist on disk), so a commit that removes a plan does not error.\n- **No file is deleted** by kref (Option A, gitignore-mirror). The live file stays\n  for the agent to read/edit; kref holds the history-clean, portable copy that\n  travels via push/pull and re-syncs on each commit.\n- Source dirs are **not** force-gitignored. The \"out of `git log`/`blame`\"\n  benefit applies to dirs the user already gitignores (superpowers' default);\n  for committed spec dirs kref is a portable mirror and the marker is a small,\n  visible, committed comment.\n- **Verified (2026-06-18):** lefthook's `files:` custom file-list command, the\n  `{files}` template, single-pattern `glob`, and `post-commit` as a hook are all\n  documented and supported (lefthook docs `configuration/files.md`,\n  `configuration/glob.md`).\n\n### D7 — Hooks: absolute path + merge (folds in the review's hook P1s)\n\n- Generated hooks invoke the **absolute path** of the running binary\n  (`os.Executable()`), not bare `kref` — fixes the `./bin/kref`-not-on-PATH break.\n- `kref hooks install --force` **merges** kref's `kref-*` commands into an existing\n  `lefthook.yml` (parse YAML, replace only kref-managed command entries under each\n  hook, preserve everything else) instead of overwriting the whole file.\n\n## 5. Components touched\n\n```\ninternal/entry/operations.go   + SetTitle op (D4)\ninternal/store/store.go        + Update(id, body, title) — Read across tiers, append SetBody/SetTitle\ninternal/bridge/bridge.go      marker parse/stamp/strip; D2 state machine; dir walk; per-file result\ninternal/hooks/hooks.go        Render(absKrefPath) with D6 post-commit; Merge(existing, generated) for D7\ncmd/kref/commands.go             ingest: MinimumNArgs(1), --skip-missing, array output; hooks install merge + os.Executable\n```\n\nEach unit keeps its Phase-1 responsibility; the marker logic lives in\n`bridge` (the file↔entry boundary), not in `store` (which stays id-addressed).\n\n## 6. Data flow (update path)\n\n```\nfile.md (… \u003c!-- kref-id: A1 --\u003e) → bridge.Ingest\n  → strip marker, body B\n  → scan.Scan(B): clean\n  → store.Get(A1): found, current body B0, title T0\n  → B == B0 \u0026\u0026 title == T0 ? no-op\n    : store.Update(A1, B, T) → entry A1 += SetBody(B)[+ SetTitle(T)]\n  → result {path, id:A1, tier, action: updated|unchanged}\n```\n\n## 7. Error handling\n\n- Missing path: error, unless `--skip-missing` (then skip-with-note in output).\n- gitleaks missing/fails: unchanged Phase-1 fail-closed (`internal/scan`).\n- Secret on marked file: error (D3), no store mutation.\n- Malformed/duplicate marker: take the **last** well-formed `kref-id` trailer;\n  ignore stray ones. A marker whose id is not 64 hex chars is treated as absent\n  (create fresh).\n- Partial batch: every path is attempted. A per-file failure (e.g. the D3\n  secret case) is recorded as its own result `{path, action: \"error\", error}`;\n  other files still ingest. The whole `ingest` invocation exits non-zero iff any\n  result is an `error`, so one secret-laden file surfaces in the hook without\n  blocking capture of the other changed plans. The result array is always\n  emitted to stdout; the non-zero exit is the signal.\n\n## 8. Testing\n\n- **entry:** `SetTitle` apply/validate/unmarshal round-trip (white-box per the\n  existing `entry_test` black-box note for the dot-import collision).\n- **bridge:** marker parse/strip/stamp; each D2 transition; dir walk; the D3\n  fail-closed case; idempotent no-op on unchanged re-ingest.\n- **store:** `Update` appends ops to the correct tier and is visible in `Get`.\n- **hooks:** `Merge` preserves a foreign `pre-commit` while replacing `kref-*`\n  (the review's `--force`-clobber regression); `Render` emits the abs path.\n- **e2e:** `git init` → `kref init` (the review's P0 repo-adoption case) → write a\n  plan under `docs/superpowers/plans/` → `kref ingest \u003cdir\u003e` → edit → re-ingest →\n  assert one entry, body updated, `action: updated`.\n\n## 9. Deferred\n\n- `kref checkout \u003cid\u003e` / materialize-from-store (only needed if we later choose\n  delete-on-ingest; Option B in the design discussion).\n- A path↔id index for fast \"which entry is this file\" without reading the file\n  (the marker is sufficient at current scale)."}]}